      <bioghist id="ref7">
         <head>Biographical/Historical Sketch</head>
         <p>Christine Ricker joined the Stanford staff in 1922; she served as director of the Student Union and the more than 40 campus dining halls from 1928 until her retirement in 1958. She also taught a course in "family living" through the School of Education. She graduated from Simmons College in 1917 with a degree in institutional administration; prior to coming to Stanford, she worked with the YWCA overseas. Ms. Ricker, who shared her campus home at 615 Mayfield Avenue with her lifelong companion Helen Vincent, died in 1986 at the age of 90.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="ref8">
         <head>Description of the Collection</head>
         <p>The diaries of Christine Ricker date from December 1941 through April 1976; included within their pages were clippings, programs, notes, letters, and other items.</p>
         <p>Some items are taped in; loose items have been removed and foldered.</p>
         <p>The diary entries concern Stanford news and personalities, World War II and other political events, Ricker's activities in the Episcopal Church, and her circle of friends, many of whom were also single working women.</p>
      </scopecontent>
